[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926854&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926854&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

As far as I can tell, this whole mess of leading digits has nothing to
do with domain communication but with interfaces between users and the
operating system.  It is the user interface's and/or system's job to
figure out if the user typed a name or an address.  It is the system's
job to make specific queries to the domain database, such as "Tell me
about this name" or "tell me about this address."  It is extremely poor
design to force the domain database to deal with "Tell me about this
thing, I don't know if it is a name or an address."  It is the domain
system's job to answer the questions, possibly asking similar, specific
questions of other domain implementations.  If the protocol for domain
implementations to talk to one another doesn't distringuish between
names and addresses, that's a bug in the protocol.  Implementations far
away from the user (and the user interface) should not have to
heursticate "Gosh, is 3Com.COM an address or a name?"

